OL,3,CAlmost #11 billion per year 'could be
OL,4,Cfreed up if people quit smoking'
OL,6,FDr Duncan Gillespie, senior research
OL,7,Ffellow at the University of
OL,8,FSheffield's school of medicine and
OL,9,Fpopulation health, said: "By reducing
OL,10,Fsmoking rates and freeing up
OL,11,Fdisposable income, policymakers have
OL,12,Fthe opportunity to alleviate smoking-
OL,13,Finduced deprivation and empower
OL,14,Findividuals to redirect funds towards
OL,15,Fessential needs.
OL,17,F"This reallocation of resources can
OL,18,Fcontribute to economic prosperity and
OL,19,Fhelp to reduce geographic inequalities
OL,20,Fin society."
